### Final Mathematical Formulations of the 11 Axioms
#### Global Definitions & Calibration Protocol- **Thresholds**: Literature-specific where available; otherwise 90th percentile from 100 phase
randomized surrogates (Theiler et al., 1992).- **Surrogates**: Phase-randomized Fourier (preserves power, destroys phase/rhythm) or amplitude
adjusted Fourier (AAFT) for nonlinear tests.- **Statistical Test**: Wilcoxon rank-sum vs. surrogates, reject H₀ at p<0.05.- **Units**: Dimensionless; series z-scored.- **Multi-entity Note**: For axioms requiring multiple networks (9–10), use external pairing (e.g., 
load paired CSVs); univariate proxies provided for Fracttalix compatibility.
1. **Matter and energy spontaneously form networks**  
∇
   **Formulation**: Clustering coefficient CC > CC_random + 0.1 (Barabási network benchmark). 
Flux F = var( R) > 0.  
   **H₀**: CC ≤ CC_random + 0.1 (Wilcoxon p≥0.05).  
   **Test**: 2D lattice Ising near critical T.  
   **Counterexample**: Isolated particles.  
   **Pilot**: N/A (simulation).
2. **Networks store resources to buffer entropy**  
   **Formulation**: I(network; resources) > I(isolated; resources) + 0.1 bits (Cover & Thomas, 1991 
benchmark).  
   **H₀**: I_network ≤ I_isolated + 0.1 (p≥0.05).  
   **Test**: Barabási–Albert vs. disconnected on resource histogram.  
   **Counterexample**: Noisy complete graph.  
   **Pilot**: N/A (simulation).
3. **Resource storage tends to increase in complexity**  
   **Formulation**: h_μ > 0.05 bits/symbol (Grassberger, 1989 symbolic dynamics).  
   **H₀**: h_μ ≤ 0.05 (p≥0.05).  
   **Test**: Evolving storage sequences.  
   **Counterexample**: Fixed storage.  
   **Pilot**: N/A (simulation).
4. **Complex emergent behaviors arise as storage capacity grows**  
   **Formulation**: Giant component φ jumps >0.5 at p_c ≈ 1/( k-1) (Erdős–Rényi, 1960).  
   **H₀**: No discontinuous jump.  
   **Test**: Erdős–Rényi varying p.  
   **Counterexample**: Subcritical p.  
   **Pilot**: N/A (simulation).
⟨ ⟩
5. **Information is encoded in structure (spatial) and rhythm (temporal)**  
   **Formulation**: I_total ≥ I_spatial + I_temporal - overlap, overlap ≤20% (dual-channel EEG 
studies, e.g., Stam 2007).  
   **H₀**: I_total ≈ max(I_spatial, I_temporal) (p≥0.05).  
   **Test**: Fractal + oscillatory vs. noise.  
   **Counterexample**: White noise.  
   **Pilot**: Bitcoin returns (I_total > max, dual encoding).
6. **Functional networks display rhythmic patterns; absence suggests dormancy**  
   **Formulation**: R = max(P(f))/total power > 0.1 (chronobiology dominant peak, Buzsáki 2006).  
   **H₀**: R identical active/dormant (p≥0.05).  
   **Test**: Periodic vs. broadband.  
   **Counterexample**: Chaotic logistic.  
   **Pilot**: HRV awake vs. sleep (R high awake).
7. **Dormant/disrupted networks cascade to sub-networks until rhythm resumes**  
   **Formulation**: P(s) ~ s^{-α} (1.5 ≤ α ≤ 2, Bak SOC range) during disruption; ends R > 0.1.  
   **H₀**: Exponential decay (p≥0.05 goodness-of-fit).  
   **Test**: Sandpile model.  
   **Counterexample**: Overdamped linear.  
   **Pilot**: N/A (simulation).
8. **Many networks exhibit fractal self-similarity across scales**  
   **Formulation**: |D_full - D_sub| < 0.1 across subscales (West scaling laws).  
   **H₀**: Variation >0.1 (p≥0.05).  
   **Test**: Higuchi full vs. windows.  
   **Counterexample**: Pure sine.  
   **Pilot**: Bitcoin (D consistent ~1.5).
9. **Networks interconnect laterally, temporally, and fractally**  
   **Formulation**: C_ms > 0.5 (multi-scale wavelet coherence, Grinsted 2004). Univariate proxy: 
coherence across window sizes.  
   **H₀**: C_ms ≤ surrogate (p≥0.05).  
   **Test**: Hierarchical vs. flat.  
   **Counterexample**: Disconnected modules.  
   **Pilot**: Multi-sensor HRV (high C_ms).
10. **Compatible networks tend to synchronize rhythms**  
    **Formulation**: Kuramoto r →1 when Δω < K (Strogatz 2000). Univariate proxy: high autocorr 
consistency.  
    **H₀**: r identical regardless Δω (p≥0.05).  
    **Test**: Coupled oscillators.  
    **Counterexample**: Detuned frequencies.  
    **Pilot**: Paired EEG channels (high r compatible).
11. **Stressors trigger cascades followed by reorganization at higher resilience**  
    **Formulation**: H_post > H_pre + 0.1 and T_rec < median pre-stress (Holling resilience).  
    **H₀**: No gain/slow recovery (p≥0.05).  
    **Test**: Volatility injection pre/post.  
    **Counterexample**: Brittle system.  
    **Pilot**: Bitcoin 2022 crash (H_post gain post-reorg).
### Falsifiability Table
| Axiom | Expression | H₀ | Criteria (p<0.05) | Fracttalix Extension | Datasets |
|-------|------------|----|------------------|----------------------|----------|
| 1     | CC > CC_random + 0.1 | CC ≤ CC_random + 0.1 | Flux high, no clustering | NetworkX 
clustering | Ising lattice |
| 2     | I_network > I_isolated + 0.1 | I_network ≤ I_isolated + 0.1 | Connected, low I | Mutual info | BA 
vs. random |
| 3     | h_μ > 0.05 | h_μ ≤ 0.05 | Growth, no entropy rise | Block entropy | Evolving storage |
| 4     | φ jump >0.5 at p_c | No jump | Subcritical φ≈0 | Giant component | Erdős–Rényi |
| 5     | I_total ≥ sum - overlap | I_total ≈ max | Noise total = max | Dual metrics | Fractal + sine, Bitcoin 
|
| 6     | R > 0.1 active | R identical | Chaotic R low | Spectral power | Periodic vs. logistic, HRV |
| 7     | Power-law α 1.5–2 | Exponential | No avalanches | Avalanche sizes | Sandpile |
| 8     | D var <0.1 | Var >0.1 | Sine inconsistent | Higuchi windows | Sine vs. pink, Bitcoin |
| 9     | C_ms > 0.5 | C_ms ≤ surrogate | Modules low | Wavelet coherence | Hierarchical, multi-HRV |
| 10    | r →1 matched | r identical | Detuned r≈0 | Kuramoto/PLV | Coupled, paired EEG |
| 11    | H gain + fast T_rec | No gain/slow | Brittle drop | Pre/post stress | Volatility injection, Bitcoin 
crash 
